article.headline: Creighton 50, Nebraska 48
article.story: LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Kellen Miliner hit a 10-foot jump shot with less than a second remaining to give Creighton a 50-48 win over Nebraska Saturday in a game in which neither team led by more than four points. Creighton (8-1) took its sixth win in seven games over in-state rival Nebraska (3-3). Creighton trailed 45-42 after Nebraska's Marcus Neal, Jr. hit a 3-pointer with 2:25 left. The Bluejays' Nate Funk made a layup to cut the Nebraska lead to one just 20 seconds later. Nebraska's John Turek then missed a pair of free throws while Dane Watt's free throws with 1:21 left gave Creighton a 46-45 lead. Tyler McKinney pushed that lead to three with a driving shot in the lane with 39 seconds remaining. Jason Dourisseau tied the game for the Huskers on a 3-pointer from the baseline that banked off the board into the basket with 26 seconds left. Turek blocked Funk's jumper with 3 seconds remaining. But the Bluejays found Miliner on the inbounds play for the game winning shot. Neal's 30- foot heave at the buzzer fell short for Nebraska (3-3). Nebraska's biggest lead of the game was 29-25 early in the second half. The game was marred by poor shooting. Nebraska hit just 35 percent of its shots while Creighton hit 34 percent. But the Bluejays heated up in the second, making 9 of their 20 shots in the second 20 minutes. Miliner led all scorers with 20 points, Funk added 13 for Creighton. Neal had 14 to lead Nebraska. Turek had 10 for the Cornhuskers who failed to score 50 points for the second consecutive game.
